'''Motoinari Kofun''' (元稲荷古墳) is an ancient Kofun located in {{ill|Kitayama, Mukocho, Muko City, Kyoto Prefecture|ja|京都府向日市向日町北山|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kitayama, Mukocho, Muko City, Kyoto Prefecture|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}}. It is part of the {{ill|Mukō Hills Kofuns|ja|向日丘陵古墳群|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Mukō Hills Kofuns|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}} and has been Historic Site1 as a National Historic Site within the {{ill|Otokuni Kofungun|ja|乙訓古墳群|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Otokuni Kofungun|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid|qid=Q135491395}}.

== Overview ==
<div class="thumb tright">
{| class="wikitable" style="background:#ffffff;text-align:center;font-size:85%;"
|+Key Kofuns in Mukō Hills<ref name="Minami2013">{{PDFlink|[http://www.kyoto-arc.or.jp/News/s-kouza/kouza242.pdf Minami Takao, "Terado Otsuka Kofun - Chief’s Tomb of the Early Kofun built in Mukō Hills"]}} (Kyoto City Archaeological Research Lecture, 2013).</ref>{{Sfn|4th Excavation Report Materials|2008}}
!No.!!name!!type!!area
|-
|1||{{ill|Itsukahara Kofun|lt=Itsukahara Kofun|lt=Gotsukahara Kofun|ja|五塚原古墳|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Gotsukahara Kofun|qq=}}||[[:en:Zenpokoenfun|Zenpokoenfun]]||91.2 m
|-
|2||'''Motoinari Kofun'''||{{ill|Zenpokoho-fun (rectangular mounded tomb)|ja|前方後方墳|lt=Zenpō-kōhō-fun|1=Zenpō-kōhō-fun|comment=doing this because I need to differentiate it in piped links too with my new interwiki tool as not the ambiguous phrase keyhole shaped kofun|1=zenpō-kōhō-fun|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Zenpokoho-fun (rectangular mounded tomb)|13=User:Immanuelle/zenpō-kōhō-fun|qq=|comment=enwiki is a redirect}}||94 m
|-
|3||[[:en:Terado Ōtsuka Kofun|Terado Ōtsuka Kofun]]||Zenpo-koen-fun||95 m
|-
|4||{{ill|Myokenyama Kofun (Muko)|ja|妙見山古墳 (向日市)|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Myokenyama Kofun (Muko)|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid|qid=Q135579270}}||Zenpo-koen-fun||114 m
|-
|5||{{ill|Densokaba Mound|ja|伝高畠陵古墳|1=Den-Takabatakeryo Kofun|lt=Den-Takabatakeryo Kofun|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Densokaba Mound|13=User:Immanuelle/Den-Takabatakeryo Kofun|qq=}}||{{ill|Round tumulus|ja|円墳|1=Round Kofun|1=Round Kofun|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Round tumulus|13=User:Immanuelle/Round Kofun|qq=|comment=enwiki is a redirect}}||65 m in diameter
|}
</div>
The mound, built on the southwestern edge of the {{ill|Kyoto Basin|ja|京都盆地|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kyoto Basin|qq=|1=Kyoto Basin|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q10883263}} near the right bank of the [[:en:Katsura River|Katsura River]], is a large zenpokoho-fun (rectangular mounded tomb) dating back to the late [[:en:3rd century|3rd century AD]]. Its name derives from the Inari shrine once located on the rear mound's summit. The site is part of a group of Kofuns in Mukō Hills, collectively known as the Mukō Hills Kofuns.

== burial ==
The mound features a {{ill|Vertical stone chamber|ja|竪穴式石室|1=Vertical Pit-Style Stone Chamber|2=ja|3=竪穴式石室|4=zh|5=豎穴式石室|1=Vertical Pit-Style Stone Chamber|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Vertical stone chamber|13=User:Immanuelle/Vertical Pit-Style Stone Chamber|qq=}} in its central rear section. Measuring 5.56 m in length and 1.9 m in height, the chamber demonstrates unique construction techniques and includes clay layers coated with vermilion. Despite historical looting, a few burial burial goods, such as iron weapons and pottery fragments, have been recovered.

== National Historic Site  ==
In 2016, Motoinari Kofun was included in the National Historic Site Historic Site of the {{ill|Otokuni Kofungun|ja|乙訓古墳群|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Otokuni Kofungun|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid|qid=Q135491395}}.<ref name="NationalHistoric Site">{{Cite web|url=http://www.bunka.go.jp/seisaku/bunkazai/shokai/shitei.html|title=National Historic Sites Database: Otokuni Kofungun|publisher=Historic Site Online}}</ref>

== Related Facilities ==
* [[:en:Kyoto University Museum|Kyoto University Museum]]: Houses and displays burial goods excavated from Motoinari Kofun.

