The mound, built on the southwestern edge of the {{ill|Kyoto Basin|ja|京都盆地|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kyoto Basin|qq=|1=Kyoto Basin|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q10883263}} near the right bank of the [[:en:Katsura River|Katsura River]], is a large zenpokoho-fun (rectangular mounded tomb) dating back to the late [[:en:3rd century|3rd century AD]]. Its name derives from the Inari shrine once located on the rear mound's summit. The site is part of a group of Kofuns in Mukō Hills, collectively known as the Mukō Hills Kofuns.

== burial ==
The mound features a {{ill|Vertical stone chamber|ja|竪穴式石室|1=Vertical Pit-Style Stone Chamber|2=ja|3=竪穴式石室|4=zh|5=豎穴式石室|1=Vertical Pit-Style Stone Chamber|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Vertical stone chamber|13=User:Immanuelle/Vertical Pit-Style Stone Chamber|qq=}} in its central rear section. Measuring 5.56 m in length and 1.9 m in height, the chamber demonstrates unique construction techniques and includes clay layers coated with vermilion. Despite historical looting, a few burial burial goods, such as iron weapons and pottery fragments, have been recovered.

== National Historic Site  ==
In 2016, Motoinari Kofun was included in the National Historic Site Historic Site of the {{ill|Otokuni Kofungun|ja|乙訓古墳群|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Otokuni Kofungun|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid|qid=Q135491395}}.<ref name="NationalHistoric Site">{{Cite web|url=http://www.bunka.go.jp/seisaku/bunkazai/shokai/shitei.html|title=National Historic Sites Database: Otokuni Kofungun|publisher=Historic Site Online}}</ref>

== Related Facilities ==
* [[:en:Kyoto University Museum|Kyoto University Museum]]: Houses and displays burial goods excavated from Motoinari Kofun.

